Three-Server Web Infrastructure Design for www.foobar.com
________________________________________
ğŸ”µ Scenario
A user wants to access www.foobar.com. The request goes through a load balancer, which distributes traffic across multiple web servers. These in turn communicate with an application and database layer to return the requested content.
________________________________________
ğŸ§± Infrastructure Components
â€¢	Server 1: Hosts the Load Balancer (HAProxy)
â€¢	Server 2: Hosts the Web Server (Nginx) + Application Server + Application Code
â€¢	Server 3: Hosts the Database (MySQL)
________________________________________
ğŸ” Request Flow
1.	User enters www.foobar.com in the browser.
2.	DNS resolves www.foobar.com to the IP of the load balancer (Server 1).
3.	HAProxy load balances incoming HTTP requests across multiple backend servers.
4.	HAProxy forwards the request to Server 2 running Nginx + Application Server.
5.	Application queries the MySQL database on Server 3.
6.	The response is sent back through HAProxy to the user.
________________________________________
ğŸ”§ Component Justification
âœ… Load Balancer (HAProxy)
â€¢	Why: Distributes traffic to avoid overloading one server.
â€¢	Distribution Algorithm: Round Robin â€“ Requests are distributed in order across available backend servers.
â€¢	Setup: Configured as Active-Active.
o	Active-Active: Multiple servers handle traffic simultaneously.
o	Active-Passive: One server is active while another waits as backup (not used here).
âœ… Web Server (Nginx) + Application Server
â€¢	Why: Handles static assets, proxies requests to the application code (Python, Node.js, PHP, etc.).
â€¢	Combined on one server for simplicity, can be scaled out later.
âœ… Application Files
â€¢	Why: These contain the logic and views of the website and live on Server 2.
âœ… MySQL Database
â€¢	Why: Stores persistent structured data for the application.
________________________________________
ğŸ—„ï¸ Database Cluster: Primary-Replica (Master-Slave)
â€¢	Primary (Master): Handles all write operations (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE).
â€¢	Replica (Slave): Handles read-only operations (SELECT), syncing from the Primary in near real-time.
In the application:
â€¢	Writes go to the Primary.
â€¢	Reads can be directed to a Replica to reduce load on the Primary.
________________________________________
ğŸš¨ Limitations and Issues
â— Single Points of Failure (SPOF)
â€¢	HAProxy (if not replicated)
â€¢	Single database (if Primary fails and no automatic failover)
â€¢	Application server (only one; if it fails, site goes down)
ğŸ” Security Issues
â€¢	No firewall to restrict malicious access
â€¢	No HTTPS/SSL encryption â€“ exposes sensitive data over the network
ğŸ“‰ No Monitoring
â€¢	No logging or alert system in place (e.g., Prometheus, Grafana)
â€¢	No health checks or status dashboards
